#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
snapperrestore — bare-metal disaster recovery from a snappersend destination
=============================================================================

Rebuilds a machine from the snapshot tree a snappersend destination server
holds for it:

    partition -> LUKS2 -> btrfs + subvolumes -> btrfs receive -> nested
    subvols -> No-COW/swapfile -> boot tier -> fstab/crypttab (UUIDs
    rewritten) -> chroot initramfs/GRUB -> verify

DISASTER RECOVERY ONLY (dead/stolen device, fresh disk, run from a live ISO
such as grml, booted UEFI); file-level recovery is out of scope — every
received snapshot is an ordinary directory on the server, browse it there.

ONE SELF-CONTAINED FILE, ON PURPOSE. In a disaster the machine that had
snappersend installed is gone; the only things the live environment needs are
Python 3 and this script. It therefore carries private copies of the
snappersend helpers it uses (logging, ssh transport, flat-config parsing, the
send/receive pipe, the destination-provisioning script). Each copy is marked
`kept in sync with snappersend`; the one that must never drift — the sudoers
provision script, which defines what the transport user may run on the
destination — is pinned equal across both files by the test suite.

SOURCE OF TRUTH — the received root snapshot IS the restore manifest:
  etc/fstab                         subvol set, mountpoints, options, swapfile
  etc/crypttab                      LUKS mapping name + unlock options
  etc/snappersend/restore-manifest  nested subvols, No-COW map, name map
                                    (written by every snappersend send run)
fstab/crypttab are TEMPLATES, not copies: structure and option strings are
preserved verbatim; every UUID is rewritten from live blkid of the freshly
created target (old and new UUIDs render at the same width, so a plain
substring replacement also preserves the operator's column layout).

Receive-vs-recreate is DERIVED, never hardcoded: every subvol the server
holds for the hostname is received (receive -> promote, never rsync); every
other fstab subvol is recreated empty. The one EXPLICIT exception (tested):
the snapper snapshot store and the swap container are always recreated empty
— old snapshot history is parented to the dead filesystem's UUID (useless),
and the swapfile is recreated No-COW. Operator input is only what the tree
cannot know: target disk, LUKS passphrase, partition sizes, server/key
bootstrap.

RESUMABILITY: a state file on the new filesystem's top level marks completed
steps; a re-run detects the prior layout, offers to resume, and skips
completed work via the markers plus per-step idempotency probes (partitions
match -> skip; subvol exists -> skip) rather than blind re-execution. Any
destination-transport failure aborts the step cleanly — partial state is
never treated as success.
"""

